Well we lived in a house, I always lived in the.. well all my young days I lived in the east part of the town. But the house I was actually born in was demolished, it got bombed, it
 got bombed during the war and well all those cottages along there were bombed but they were never rebuilt. They were very badly bombed and they weren't worth repairing by that time you see. They weren't rebuilt and it's just a vacant site now but it was 
down what they call Land Lane, opposite where you come out of Priory Street}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2715693\charrsid7434366 . You know Prior}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
y Street where the Catholic church is, well opposite there is a lane, well it'll be a road soon because they've been building down there, but when I lived down there,
 there weren't many cottages there then, there were fields down at the bottom part and it was a dead end, it didn't lead anywhere, only to a big brickyard which doesn't exist now, and then there were some footpaths, well the footpaths are still there. You
 go round and you get into the park that way. Well I lived up at the top end. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15684215\charrsid7434366 
As I say those cottages were bombed in the early part of the war and they were never rebuilt and it's just a vacant site there now. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 But I lived there until I was about 10 I suppos
e and then I moved on to East Hill. Course I always went to school in that part of the town you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Were you born in the house, were you born at home in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh yes of course because people were then. Maternity homes didn't exist or if t
hey did they were few and far between. There were none in Colchester. I mean people used to have these big families, well there was no such thing as going away from home. People used to just have to manage, they got used to it, well they must have got use
d
 to it. Because of course the hospital system was entirely different. When you were ill, if a person was ill, apart from emergencies or accidents what used to happen in Colchester and I've no doubt it was the same system everywhere else, if you thought th
a
t you.. if the doctor said you should have it, then they collected in the street and then there'd be what they called a pound day when people would give pounds of groceries, stuff that wouldn't perish. You see, well that was how the hospitals were support
ed. And if you were wanting to go into hospital you had to go to these\'85
 somebody who was a subscriber and ask them would they'd give you a ticket, recommendation and that's how you got in hospital you see then. I expect that was the same system anywhere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Yes that was the case in London
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Yes well that's how it used to be here I know. You see the wealthy people used to subscribe.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Tell me at your school, were there children from very different types and class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well you can say that in thos
