\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well that'd all depend on how much they w
anted and how much room they'd got to store it. Besides if they knew that the boys were coming round regularly you see, they'd only get enough. Besides not many people used to buy much quantity of anything then because their money was so, had to be so bal
anced out. I mean there weren't many people in those days, except the real well}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13900602\charrsid7434366 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
off people that stocked up coal in the summer. Well for one thing a lot of people hadn't got room. Of course a lot of the big houses had a real coal collar and they would get th
eir stock in but the ordinary people, very few ordinary people had a lot. They used to buy week to week. Because, well, their money balanced out better that way, and not only that, there didn't use to be the difference in the prices. I think well I never 
remember hearing people say 'Oh, we must get ou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13900602\charrsid7434366 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
 coal in before so-and-so because it'll be dearer after that! There wasn't, didn't used to be so, you see. So people didn't used to have new stocks of fuel, that just enough to last them one week or so, you know. Most people..
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did your mother have a sink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well in our particular case we lived in a rather old-fashioned house and she didn't and we didn't have inside water. We had to go outside and the tap was just outside, the drain was there. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4000104\charrsid7434366 
Course it meant that you had to open your door and you let the cold in the winter, but of course that was a common thing in thousands of houses in Colchester like that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Thousands and thousands.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 And what sort of lighting did she have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well we had to start
 off with, course we had like most people paraffin lamps and then of course later on we got on to gas but of course electric light, very few people had electric light. Even the churches and schools hadn't got it. Got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13900602\charrsid7434366 g}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 as. Course this new school that I went to, well of course we used to just gaze up at the electric lights and think how wonderful they were. I think the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13900602\charrsid7434366 Moot}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366  Hall had got them but all these other buildings had got gas. Some of them were only naked gas }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13900602\charrsid7434366 je}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 ts. That St...When I went to St. James School and this other chapel school as well, they were just naked gas jets. Weren't even incandes}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13900602\charrsid7434366 ce}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 nt m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13900602\charrsid7434366 antles}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 . Oh no. Then of course the incandescent mantles came in later. There's a very few people had electricity.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did your mother bake her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 She didn't, no. My mother didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did she do any bottling of fruit or preserves or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 She might have made a little home-made jam but as we hadn't got a big enough garden to grow our own fruit, she didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh I was going to ask you that, when I was asking you about the house. Did you have any garden at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well we had some, but we used to keep it for flowers. It wasn't enough for anything else. It's like mine out here now, you see, I don't attempt to grow vegetab
les because well they don't do any good in back gardens and, but, I never lived anywhere where there was a big garden. And I mean it's surprising now in Colchester how many houses haven't got hardly any garden at all, worth speaking of. I was surprised I 
h
ad occasion to see come back ways two or three years ago and I was greatly surprised and I had thought those houses all had got nice gardens. And instead of that they'd got the tiniest place. Just... one big shed on and they've got nothing left. A lot of 
houses like that. There's some across the road here and they've only got just the very tiniest place and just about enough to dry the linen on. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13900602\charrsid7434366 
In fact there's some houses, I don't know I don't know, when there were no launderettes, no washing machines or a
nything and when you think of all the thick clothing that people used to wear, and big families, how on earth they used to get the linen dry well, of course, they didn't get it dry, they had to have it indoors.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did your mother wash one special day every week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Oh yes, oh yes, and didn't we know it. Of course it was always Monday. Everybody always washed on Monday and of course it was a ... in most families a sort of day of upheaval.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 How was it in your home? Was it like that in your home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh it was a bit of an upheaval you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Where did she wash? In the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Yes, and we used to live in the front room on washing day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Yes. Only on washing day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 On washing day we used to live in the front room. Normally we didn't 
live in the front room, not when I lived on East Hill. We didn't live in the front room normally, we used to go in on Sundays. Course that was the common thing you know. People didn't used their front rooms, not normally, unless you had friends come or sp
ecial occasions, you lived in the back. Never mind what the outlook was like. That was the.... and but washing day we used to go in the front room. That did used to be a bit of an upheaval. Well it was in everybody's, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 You remember how she used to do the washing in your home? How did she do it, I mean would she heat the water in a.. How would she do it?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well people used to have to heat the water in a copper you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 She would do that, would she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 In a copper and of course there were no gas coppers or if there were any they were few and far between.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 So did she heat it on the grate then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well you see they used to.. there was a fire underneath the copper and they used to pound the linen with copper sticks, what they call 
copper sticks and pounding it about and then they'd take it all out and then there'd have to be another lot to rinse at the end and then they'd have to go through the mangle, if you'd got a mangle, not everybody had one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did your mother have a mangle, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 She had a wringer you know and some people had these great cumbersome mangles. I daresay you've seen them in museums.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well I've heard about them. People used to take in mangling
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh yes a lot of people used to take them in
, but that was more, that was more when they were half dry they used to take them in. I don't think many people used to take them in wet. A lot of people used to take mangling in to earn a few coppers and they used to be great big cumbersome mangles, you 
know, of course, they've sort of died out. I don't suppose they exist, well I don't suppose they can be bought now, don't suppose they could. Of course in those days they were great cumbersome things and of course washing day was a, well it was
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did she do ironing on the same day or the next day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well it depended if they got dry. I mean if they weren't dry they didn't get ironed till later on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 If they didn't get dry, what did she do with them then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well you used to just have to.. when yo
u went to bed at night you had to leave a fire and put them round what's called a horse. And then you'd got to hang them on lines in the room in your living room. I mean there was no such thing as launderettes and everything was soaked, there were no dete
r
gents or like that. And I mean people used to wear such hefty clothes especially in the winter. And then I mean not only was it the washing, they must have been terrible to get dry. And of course, now people would think nothing of which day they washed be
c
ause its such a simple business today and they can just put them into soak and.. and of course in those days a lot of people wouldn't have dreamed of having linen hanging out on a Sunday. Oh no, that was considered.... my mother wouldn't and she didn't pr
ofess to be, well she used to go to church and all that but she never professed to be... But it was sort of looked.. that you didn't do it, not many people. I'm not going to say that they didn't in big cities
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 But not in Colchester.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 But not in ty
pical, of course I'm taking Colchester as a typical town you see. I mean if somebody saw that somebody got some linen out on Sunday, they'd be shocked. Fancy linen out on a Sunday. That's how it was you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did your mother go shopping, or did she have most things bought?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well you could sort of do either. She used to do most of her own shopping, but I remember later on when she'd got older, she used to have things delivered, because of course in those days they used to do parcels up and you had 
lots of brown paper and string. Everybody'd got loads of brown paper and string.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 You mean the things were delivered done up in a parcel were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh yes. And of course shopping in those days was of course easy. I mean they used to be open late 
at night you see. I mean people could go out shopping after they'd done work. Course we know it was all... there wasn't any necessity for it when you look back. But of course there it was, just people put up with it and they didn't think anything of it. I
 
mean I remember here on Saturday nights, they didn't close till 9, some later than that. People'd go out 8 o'clock at night. But you see, there's another way to look at that. Lots of people didn't get their wages till they left off, which might be, say th
e
y had Saturday afternoon off, they got their wages on Saturday just before they left off. Well where they were living a hand to mouth existence which most people were, I mean they relied on one week's money to buy their things, which of course even in tho
s
e days thousands still have to or they do at any rate, well that meant that people who didn't leave off till teatime, they got their wages Saturday teatime, they'd got to go and spend it Saturday night. Well the shops used to be open here till 9 and I thi
nk in London a lot of them were open till 11 and 12 at night. Well I know they were because of what I've read and what I've heard my own relations say. And then of course, well even myself, before the war I worked for a little while in .......
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 How can you tell me the year you left school? Roughly speaking or how old you were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 1911.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 1911. And what was the first job you had after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 In the \{illegible\} and mineral water bottling trade.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Yes, and can you tell me your hours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Most jobs in those days very long hours and very poor money which of course everybody's was and everybody's hours were long. It didn't matter what they did they all had long hours. I mean even office workers had longer, much longer hours than they
 do today. Nobody had Saturday morning off, whoever they were and whatever they did. It just wasn't heard of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 And in your particular job what kind of work did you have to do? Can you describe to me a day's work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well to start with I used to go out on the vans and..
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 What time in the morning would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well I was fortunate in some ways. The employers that I worked for didn't like early mornings which was fortunate for us because we didn't start work until about half past eight. And 
of course we had to work later at night but we didn't have to go home to breakfast. Course that was very unusual, most people did. The great majority of people did unless they were office workers and even some of those. If the firm started, I mean Paxmans
 for instance, well if the men started work at 6 or half past, well the office staff had to start as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 But go on telling me about your own particular job. You'd start off on the vans you say and what would you do next?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well I used to go out o
n the vans delivering and of course we didn't have any half day then, half days weren't compulsory, they came later, but it wasn't compulsory and I used to go out then mainly on town deliveries. Mainly, sometimes out in the country. The country was a very
 
long day because they were horse drawn vehicles, course there were no cars, there were no commercial motors, not in this part of England any rate and there weren't many anywhere but they just didn't exist in this part of England. And firms that had very l
ong journeys, often their horsemen would have to start ever so early in the morning. And sometimes of course they had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13900602\charrsid7434366 2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
 horses if the journey was long and the load heavy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Yes did you have }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13900602\charrsid7434366 2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366  horses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 No we only had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13900602\charrsid7434366 1}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366  because we didn't do the long j
ourney not so far as some firms but for instance I knew a man who worked for a firm, they used to deliver at Harwich and Dovercourt for instance. Well to do a journey in a day they had to start terribly early in the morning and finish up late at night. Th
ey used to have to take, course it was the common thing, they used to take the horse's food in a nosebag and a pail for water which was slung underneath the lorry..
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 But yours didn't have to do that then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Not in town, not in town, only in the country
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 You did on the country?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh yes because you couldn't get back in the middle of the day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 And then when you'd got to the places, did you take in the bottles, is that what you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 It was all retail trade you see. We used to do priva
te trade at houses, we didn't do any... they hadn't got any public houses, it was all retail family trade.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Were the orders already placed or did you have to go and ask..?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh they were ordered the previous week you see. Well of course in those da
ys nobody paid anything on bottles. I can't think how these mineral water, mineral water people used to make a profit, make much profit. But of course they did, because their's is largely a seasonal trade and I mean they depended to a large extent on a ho
t
 summer. Of course we used to get hot summers, but I mean if we didn't get a hot summer, their trade wasn't so good. And they never charged on their bottles. Well what used to happen, I don't know whether you've ever seen these glass bottles with a marble
 
in, used to be the old-fashioned ginger beer bottle. Well there's not many about. They had them in museums sometimes. I had one in my possession and I was foolish enough not to hang on to it. I mean I just let it go, I didn't sell it or anything. I mean n
o
w I wish I'd either kept it curiosity or given it to the Museum. It was ginger beer and lemonade were the two. All these squashes and things weren't highly thought of. You couldn't you couldn't buy them in grocer's shops like you can today and ginger beer
 and lemonade were the two main...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Those were the two you carried.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
They were the two main things. Well ginger beer at a penny a bottle, no charge on the bottle. Well about 50 per cent of the bottles never came back. Boys broke them to get the mar
bles out because marbles was a popular game at certain times of the year. You hardly see anyone play them now. They did and they used to break the bottles to get the marbles out or people would use the bottles turn them upside down, make a border on a gar
den path. You got, in a long garden, there might have been }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3540722\charrsid7434366 100}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
 bottles all to make... and the manufacturers didn't care. I mean apparently they didn't care. I have even seen, I have even seen these mineral water bottles made into money boxes. Course it must
 have been very difficult because you see they used to have a, what we call a kink in the neck and these bottles to make a money box out of them, they had to be very carefully cut, to make a slot big enough for a penny to go in. Well of course probably to
 
make that slot they might break a dozen bottles before they got one. Of course the great drawback to that form of saving was that the child could see how much money he'd got. And that was a temptation to smash the bottle to get the money out. You couldn't
 
get the money out until you'd smashed the bottle but the temptation must have been very great when they looked and saw the halfpennies and pennies in there. Anyway it seems wonderful that the mineral people, that the mineral water people made the profits 
t
hat they did. Under the circumstances, because, as I say, there was no charge on bottles and the losses must have been enormous besides all the risks of a poor summer, a poor wet summer, a cold summer. Course you didn't get so many cold summers then I'll 
a
dmit but on the other hand children hadn't got the money to buy too much of it. But any rate in those days there was no charge on bottles and well on the country rounds every firm that had country trade which of course they all did, grocers and all the Co
-
op and everybody, when the horseman went out on a journey. Course as I say some of them went before breakfast if they'd got a long journey, but normally they'd say go before breakfast and get their vans loaded and their horses all ready and they'd go home
 to breakfast, then they'd come back and start off.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 And was it like that with you because you didn't go home for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 We didn't go before breakfast you see. We didn't do any... our journeys weren't long enough to demand that. Of course on 
their country journeys they used to be late at night very often, but not as late as some people. Anyway the town journeys, well they didn't amount to much you see because they were all local and they you'd get home to dinner, you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 And you used to get home to dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Oh yes, expect when we went in the country. Of course when you went out on a country journey, you just had to take your food because there wasn't anywhere you could get anything. There was no cafes anywhere and well of course the
 procedure then was that all the public houses on the road used to have, not exactly stables, but they'd have a big shed outside where if it was wet the horse could stand underneath you see and put the nosebag on the horse and, as I say, they carried a pa
i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3540722\charrsid7434366 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366  and the pub would give them a pail of water for the horse and the man, the man and the boy who was with him
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 That's very good, you've written down the names of books.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 If there's anything you don't understand, just ask me, you see. 'Course I can't think of all the books.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 No, but I'm very glad you did that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Those were the principal ones that people used to have. There's another thing I had thought about, but I haven't had time to do it and that would be the kind of sweets that we used to eat, 'cos I think that could be interesting
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well, what do you remember about the kind of sweets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, well, naturally I remember a lot, because that's a thing you would remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 You were keen on sweets, were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, yes... well, w
hen I could afford them, and 'course, children didn't have much ... they didn't have much pocket money, but I mean, there were an enormous number of varieties of sweets to be had. Enormous number. And there were an enormous number of sweet shops. And then
,
 of course, you had the people in Colchester ... well, in other towns, too, no doubt, who made their own homemade ones. I mean, there was one family in Colchester, they were all members of one family, that's all died out now, and they were all rock makers
.
 They used to make the most delicious rock. And besides them in the shop, there was 4 members of them. I could remember 4 of them having shops in different parts of the town and they were well known for their rock. Then the used to have stalls up in the H
i
gh St. as well, on Saturdays, and visitors used to buy it and take it back because it was so good. But they all died out and if they had any sons they didn't take it up. But they've been died out a long... but when I went to school they were very famous a
nd it was good. It was good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 What did it look like? Was it coloured with writing in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Oh, some of them were coloured. Oh, yes. And then, see, they had what they call ... sort of what they call a plain stickjaw, what they used to call stickjaw, tha
t was homemade toffee, you see. And they'd have that in the shop on a tray and they'd break it up with a hammer, you see, that was ... but it was all good. All made from good sugar and ... well, it might have been margarine, perhaps, not butter, but still
 
butter was cheap. But in any case, it was all good. You can't get sweets like it now. There's a man that has a stall in the market here now, he makes homemade sweets, but there's absolutely no comparison with his homemade sweets there with what these othe
rs used to be, no comparison whatever. But that firm - well, it wasn't a firm, exactly, it was a
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Could you just repeat that, about the firm? Just that little bit, 'they never sold out ...'
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 They never sold their businesses, they simply died out an
d they didn't sell their businesses and hand on their recipes to anybody else. And one very curious thing about all that family, they not only made all this good rock - 'course, they sold other sweets as well - they were all taxidermists, because in those
 
days people used to have a lot of stuffed birds. I forgot to put that in about what the houses were like, the homes. But they did, they used to have stuffed birds and pet dogs and cats and all sorts of things. And all this family, they had once ... there 
were 4 of them in business, what I can remember and they all had once ... they all had a kind of a double-fronted shop, one side of the shop would be sweets and the other side would be all their }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3540722\charrsid7434366 paraphanalia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 . It's a bit of a queer mixture when you come to l
ook back, but we hope they didn't make the sweets and do the other job both at the same time. But we ... of course, as children it never occurred to us anything about that. All we knew was they sold good sweets.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 You had this very lovely fireplace, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
And fluted ... what we called the hobs at the side, all fluted, and that used to be one of my jobs to blacklead that, when that was used. And we used our front room more than some people did, it wasn't as sacred with us, because our kitchen was ve
ry small and not only that, my mother hadn't got that ... she wasn't so houseproud as some people. You know what I mean. And the consequence was that we used our front room more and in any case, to get ... we lived on the street, right on the street, and 
we had to go to the front room to get to the other, so if we'd wanted to keep it so sacred it wouldn't have been possible. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3540722\charrsid7434366 
Well, anyway, the consequence was, we used our front room more than some - in fact, I think in the winter time we used to use it every
 Sunday - and washing day used to be such an upheaval that we often used it on washing day as well because of the kitchen, you know ... washing days used to be a real big upheaval. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
But that had one of these most elaborate fireplaces and it used to be a ...
 I know, it used to be my job to blacklead that, and it used to be a business, it really did. It was a real business, because, you know, with all these embossed flowers, and things. And the curious thing is - of course, there's none of those fireplaces ab
out now, or hardly any - I saw in a shop on East Hill a week or two ago, ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Can you tell me if your front room had these rugs like you mention here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 The rugs? Oh, yes, there used to be - I shouldn't think there's many people make them now, I shouldn't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did your mother make them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well, I don't know whether my mother actually did, because she used to go out to work, and that, but the brother I had who was an invalid he used to make a lot. Of course, when they were made properly 
they were splendid rugs. Of course, they harboured the dirt, but I mean they wanted a lot of beating to keep them clean. But people who got expert and good at it - I didn't used to do much, I hated it, I haven't got no patience I suppose. But this brother
,
 you see, he had a lot of spare time and he used to make a lot. Because you could buy the pieces of cloth from the clothing factories, you see, there's always been clothing factories in Colchester, and you could buy the cloth at ever go ... well, you know
,
 ridiculous price. And people used to make ... people who were good at it used to make lovely designs. See, they'd work a pattern and it would be ... the main colours were black and grey, but they would work red and other colours in and make a really nice
 design.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did your brother do his own designs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well, he wasn't all that good at designing, but he used to make some good rugs. And, of course, they ... well, they lasted forever, nearly. And especially if people had them down in their front rooms 
where they didn't use them, of course, they never wore out. And they never wore out in a bedroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 What sort of tools did he use for making them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, they had a special tool. It was a ... well, they used to call it a needle, but it was more like 
an awl, a bran awl, more after that style. It was a steel thing in a handle and you pressed a lever and you put your piece of cloth ... this thing, although they called it a needle it was more like a bran awl, and it would be about the size of a medium si
z
ed screwdriver or the size of a big table knife, or a medium sized table knife ... and your pressed this lever and then you put your piece of ... - 'course, you got to cut all this cloth up to the right size beforehand, that was a tedious job, but of cour
s
e, people used to do it on winter nights and then, you see, they'd get the children, perhaps, to cut the cloth and the mother if she had the time, or any of the others, would make the rug, you see. And they used to put this piece of cloth in the - when yo
u
 pressed the lever, you see, it opened the thing, and you put your piece of cloth in there and then you pushed the point through this hessian. You see, you had a sheet of hessian, like this, and you'd have to fold that. See, you'd have to fold it, and you
 
pushed this tool through there, and you pushed your piece of cloth. And then you carried along that line, and then you started the next line. Of course, until you got used to it you could make a mess up. You could make a rug that looked horrible when it w
a
s finished because you might not have put them close enough, but people who got used to it, and experts, they used to make ... But I never remember them being sold in a shop, but people who knew a good rug makers - and if they couldn't make them themselve
s, or didn't want to - they would order one from somebody who was good at it, you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did your brother take any orders?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 No, I don't think he ever ... I don't remember him doing that, but he made a lot. I remember we had one... well, it was too 
big, really, it was so heavy that you had to be strong to lift it and shake it. You really did. It was big enough for two, but then, you see, we had... this elaborate fireplace was a very big, wide fireplace, the consequence was it needed a big, wide hear
t
hrug. But it was a terrific thing to shake, because they were terribly heavy. And of course, most of them were lined at the back, as well. Well, it wasn't a good job unless it was lined at the back. Some people didn't line them, but you reckoned, to have 
a really good job they wanted lining. And then that'd all help them to last longer, of course. But I shouldn't think there's many people do them, now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did you have a piano in your front room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 We didn't have one. We couldn't afford one. But of cou
rse, people who were... people did. A lot of people did if they could. We'd've had one, but of course, they were frightfully expensive.
