\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did you sing at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 No. No, we did
n't, none of us did. But of course, people would if they could, they'd have a piano, but of course they were frightfully expensive.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Yes, of course, they were. I was just looking at these things about the books. Are these magazines and things you menti
oned ones you actually read yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Oh, yes, because, you see, boys would leave... boys, perhaps, would take one kind and then they would lend them and pass them on and all that sort of thing, 'till in the end, of course, they'd be just work out with being passed around.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did you do the same with books, or did you belong to a library?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well, I did belong to the library at one time because there happened to be a library here. But of course, in lots of the villages there weren't any libraries. There weren't any at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 But here in Colchester you did belong to one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 There was one. Yes, I did, and used to read the juvenile books.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did you have to pay to belong?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well, it only used to be a very nominal sum for the ticket every 
year. I think it was only a penny a year, but it was only just a nominal sum and a ticket lasted a year. But it was a funny thing. I was always a great reader and yet some of the most classical books, I've never read them. And I had some of them as prizes
, but I didn't like them when I started to read, I didn't like them and I just didn't carry on with them. And yet they were classics. But I was funny that way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did you have books in your home? Did your parents own books?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well, of course, everybo
dy had books, you know what I mean. Everybody had books. There wasn't a home without books because, you see, children used to get them as prizes. And not only that, people used to take care of things, you see. I mean, the mothers and the fathers, perhaps 
had got books that they had when they were young, but people used to take care and, you see, they didn't...}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7434366  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
when they got tired of them they didn't throw them away and destroy them, or very seldom. Then, you see, another thing... sometimes... you see, peopl
e didn't live so long as they do now. Well, sometimes, you see, if the father or the mother's parents died, or other relatives, they would inherit a lot of stuff which, even if they didn't particularly want it they wouldn't do away with it for sentimental
 
reasons. Or they'd say, 'that was my mother's', or, 'that was my father's, oh, I must keep that', even if they hadn't got any real use for it. Well, the consequence was such things as books and ornaments and photos and pictures would all go to the collect
i
on in the front room, still. And if you hadn't got a bookcase it used to be the fashion to range your books all round the table. You'd perhaps... of course, depending on how many you'd got, the more you wanted to put on the table, of course, the bigger th
e
 pile you had to have in each. And then, you see, the middle of the table would have photo frames and... 'cos, of course, everybody's photo had to go in a frame and if it couldn't go on the wall it had to stand... well, anywhere where there was room for i
t, 'cos, of course, that was the fashion. Everywhere was chock a block.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
I wanted to ask you about when you went in to your first job and you were going out on the waggon, you know, with the minerals. Then you said you got fed up with all that ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well, you see, because you were exposed to the weather, because the only sort of vans that I can remember - well, mainly - that were covered over, were bakers' vans and things that really must be kept dry. But quite a big proportion of the vans weren't co
vered. They'd have a cloth. They'd have a tarpaulin thing which they could - like they do now - which they could put over stuff if the weather was too wet and it had got to be protected, but there weren't so many covered vans. And the drivers were... ofte
n, you see, the drivers were totally exposed to the weather.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 What did you cover you}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003811\charrsid7434366 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 self with, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well, you see, they used to have a rug for your knees. A rug around your knees. A waterproof rug.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 What about your head? What did you wear on your head?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well, you'd wear... you see, caps were the most popular thing in those days. Well, the men might wear a bowler hat... some men might wear a bowler hat, but the trilbies... there weren't any trilbies about. It was... most working men wore 
a cloth cap or a bowler.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 And then what year was it that you got a job inside the factory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well, that would have been about the early part of 1914, I expect. It was before the War.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 What hours did you work when you took that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, we
ll, we used to start at half past 8 because, as I said, the employers I worked for didn't like early mornings, but that was most exceptional to start so late. I mean a lot of people used to have to go before breakfast. It was quite common to go before bre
akfast and come home for breakfast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 And what time did you finish, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well, the average time was... the official time would be about 6 o'clock at night. Of course, if you were out on the... out in the country, you know, you didn't know what time you might be home.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 But when you were working in the plant?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
When you were inside your time would be about 6 o'clock at night. But Fridays and Saturdays was always much later. Perhaps about 8, Fridays and Saturdays. Then, of course, later on it got modified so it got down to about 6 every night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 What pay did you get when you had that job, can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well, when I started... when I left school I started on 4 shillings a week, which was... it was the normal... it was sort of the n
ormal wage then, for a boy leaving school at 14, was 4/- a week. And then after a year you often got a shilling extra, after a year. After much deliberation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 And in 1914?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well, in 1914 I think...I think in 1914 I would probably be getting about 16/- a week, I expect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did you belong to a trade union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, no. No, there wasn't much...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did anybody in your factory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 No. There wasn't... it was only a small firm, and not only that, there wasn't much of the union in those days. Not a
nything nearly. I don't think that probably in all Colchester... 'course, I don't know, not really, but probably in all Colchester there was probably only }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003811\charrsid7434366 1}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366  or 2 firms that had... Same as Paxman's, which wasn't such a... 'course, Paxman's wasn't such a big
 firm as it is now, although it was a most important... it was very important to Colchester because it was one of the main sources of employment. And I don't suppose even they - they may have had, but I don't think so. I mean because, you see, there was n
ever... when there was a general election, or even a local election, it was only Conservatives and Liberals. Labour, there was no Labour in Colchester for - oh, not 'till after the War. Not '}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003811\charrsid7434366 t
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 ill after the first War. And the people who were really what you 
call Labour people, oh, they didn't amount to anything. I mean, they just sort of... well, they didn't exist, not here. And of course, it didn't exist out in the agricultural districts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 What difference did it make to your outlook on life, do you think, starting work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well, I don't suppose it made much difference, you simply accepted the fact that you'd finished school. Most people hated it and they were... I didn't hate it, but most people hated it. Well, the biggest majority hated it and, of cou
rse, they looked forward to the day when they'd leave and be free, or when they thought they'd be free. They actually, if they'd only have known it, of course, their schooldays were probably some of their best days. But still, they didn't know that and of
ten they hated school so much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 But you didn't feel very differently about... ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well, you just accepted the fact that you'd got to work for a living and that's all there was about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did you meet kinds of people that you'd not come into contact with before when you worked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well, not where I worked because it was only a small firm, so I didn't really... I didn't have the experience that a person would in a big firm. But of course, even if those days, I mean... well, even if people worked
 on a big firm I don't know that there was much in it from that point of view because everybody... the main thing in life was to earn a living. And there wasn't much leisure. So I don't know, really, that there was much in it. All you felt about it was th
at you were free from school. You were free from school and you earned some money, that's all it was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did you pay into any clubs or societies at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well, I didn't, because... Of course, friendly societies were a great thing in those days becau
se... well, you see, there was nothing else. There was no... But it so happened that just about the time I left school, just about that time, the health insurance came in and you had to pay to that. Well, the consequence was, you see, a lot of people didn
't go in for the friendly societies then because they'd got to pay the National Health - although, of course, it wasn't much in those days. I don't know what it was, but of course, it wasn't much. I mean, now, a man in work now is paying just on }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10247317 \'a3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 1 a week i
n contributions. Of course, he gets more benefit if he needs it, but none the more for that so far as the friendly societies were concerned. You see, when the National Health Insurance came in it did mean that a lot of the people who would normally have g
one into the friendly societies didn't go, because, for one thing it would have been an extra contribution to find which was hard enough out of 4/- a week, and... well, the necessity didn't seem the same, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Yes. You were saying it used to be one Sunday afternoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 They would assemble somewhere with their banners, which were most magnificent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 All the friendly societies in Colchester?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Yes. And they would ... the Mayor and Corporation would go, and also the Fire Brigade, and they wou
ld all march to ... it would be a different church. Of course, they had to select a church that was big, would hold a lot of people, and they'd have a different ... sort of do the big churches in rotation. So they'd go to a certain one this year and anoth
e
r one the next and then get round. But it used to be ... 'course, that was an annual event. But of course, there's no such thing, not in Colchester, now, and I think it's died out in a lot of places. But of course, it did used to be a great thing, because
 ... well, without the friendly societies, of course, I don't know what people would've done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
About your own job again. Can you tell me something about you, yourself, in this first job you had. What did your work actually consist of when you worked inside the firm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well, it was in the bottling department, we bottled the stuff up, you see. It was a really hard ... comparatively hard job in those days because they hadn't got the machinery, for one thing, that they've ... 'course, they've got most el
aborate machinery, some of these places, today. And even this last place where I worked at, they'd got some fairly good machinery although, of course, no comparison with the huge, gigantic concerns, but still, they had got some pretty good .... 'Cos they'
d
 ... they had modernized their plant to a good extent, but of course, as they were still a comparatively small firm they hadn't done it like some. But in those days, where I was, you see, there wasn't much, it wasn't very mechanized at all. Not really. Yo
u
 can say it was practically all hand work, and, of course, some of it was pretty heavy. But then, of course, the same thing applied to so many other things. And I just ... you see, I just grew up with it, and didn't sort of know any different. I never tho
ught about anything different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 What did you do in the evenings after work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well, as I say, Friday and Saturday you'd work late. And sometimes, some of the other nights you'd have to be late. 'Course, you didn't get anything extra for it, staying late, you didn't get anything.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 If you got off at about 6, what did you do, for example?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well, I think my main thing was, I used to do a fair share of housework. I wasn't actually compelled to. We did have odd jobs, but I used to do more than I 
was compelled to because I liked it. And as I say, my mother used to go out to work quite a bit - well, when she could - and I used to like housework and I used to do quite a bit. And of course, I used to do a tremendous lot of reading. But that's about a
ll because there were no ... there weren't any pictures, not for years, even if you could've afforded it. Well, I could've afforded it sometimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 What kind of housework did you particularly enjoy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well, general housework. Do sort of anything - cl
eaning windows, and .. 'Course there used to be a lot of brass to clean; and fireplaces. 'Course, that was a horrible job, really, but then everybody had it. But you can't wonder that ... 'course, the women ... well, they did, I mean, their lives were jus
t slavery, really. I mean, in most cases ... 'course, when the children grew up they got things a bit easier.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 I wanted also to ask, when you had meals in the family, where did you eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, we used to eat in the living}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003811\charrsid7434366  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 room. We didn't eat in the f
ront room, unless we were living in there on a Sunday. But I think most Sundays in the winter we used to live in the front room, simply because ... not that there was any special reason, but we lived on a main street, down East Hill which of course, even 
i
n those days, had a fair amount to see. You know, people passing by, although, of course, traffic was nothing in comparison to what it is now. But still, there was traffic. I mean, it was one of the main roads of the town. And of course, you saw more if y
ou were in the front room. Whereby, if you were in the back room ... well, you only look out on your garden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 So you all used to eat in the front room in the winter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Most Sundays we used to go in the front room in the winter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 What about in the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
In the week, well, we didn't often... we could if we wanted to because it wasn't kept a holy of holies in our family. But of course, lots of people, they just wouldn't allow the children to go in. They wouldn't. it was absolutely forbidden. O
f course, one reason for that might have been ... course a lot of that was tradition that had been handed on. But of course, there was another side to it, that with wages being as low as they were they couldn't replace worn out stuff so easily. The conseq
uence was all the best things were in the front room, and, of course, they had to be taken care of. That was one reason, although the main reason was tradition, and being houseproud.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 When you had your meals did you all sit down at the same time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 We used to in our family, but of course, a lot of families couldn't have done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 I mean in your particular family, that's what I'm keen to find out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, we used to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did you all have the same places at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Yes. Yes, it used to be the common, recognised thing, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Was your father served first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well, I suppose he was. I don't remember, but I suppose he was, because it used to be a custom. And another thing, often the man had got to get back to work at dinnertime and 
... whereby the children, perhaps, hadn't got to get back to school so early. Oh, it used to be the custom. Father was the boss. That was a recognised ... nobody questioned that, I mean.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Do you remember how your mother served a meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well, no, not particularly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 You don't remember if she put it in dishes and put it on the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Oh, yes, we served it from the table. We did because we hadn't got the same facilities as some people. But in any case that was the custom. We }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12415164\charrsid7434366 used }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 to serve from the table, not to dish it up and bring it in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 And if there was a joint of meat, who would carve up the meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well, in our case my mother generally used to, but it used to be reckoned to be the man's job, more often than not.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 And who would serve you all, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well, Mother would do all that, me Father didn't used to do that, although I believe in some of the better - off families it used to be the father's job. He was the big man, you know, in some of these places.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did you all have the same food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Yes, I think so. Well, in ordinary working class families there wasn't much picking and choosing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Your father didn't have special food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, no, no. If there was something you didn't like, well, I expect you just had to go without.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 If your mother served up something and you didn't want it, were you compelled to try and eat it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, I don't think we were in our family, but of course, a lot of parents did. They just insisted. They just insisted on obedience and it 
wouldn't matter if the child screamed, or what he did, it'd be, 'oh, it's good for you, you must eat it. You won't leave the table 'till you've had it'. That's how it used to be in some families, but I don't think that we were pressed like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Do you remember what games you, particularly, and your brothers used to play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well, there used to be a lot of games ... things done that are not done now. One of the things, which of course, couldn't take place now, boys and girls, too, used to bowl hoops
 in the road, but of course, that couldn't take place now. Boys would have iron ones made at the black}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12415164\charrsid7434366 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
mith's and girls would have wooden ones with a wooden stick. And the boys would have an iron stick in a handle and they would bowl that ... and the girls
 would have a wooden one, and ... 'Course, it was a dangerous thing, really, but still there were horses in those days, you see, and not fast moving traffic. And then things like ... certain games used to have their seasons. Nobody knew why, you know what
 
I mean, but in the spring suddenly the whips and tops would come out. You know what I mean? Whips and tops? And they'd come out in the spring as if it was on a calendar. And marbles, that was a kind of a seasonal game. But these whips and tops, I have rea
d
 about that why these things used to come out at certain seasons. They originated in the back ... centuries back in connection with religion and to whip a top, they were whipping the devil. But children didn't know that when you went to school, I've heard
 about that since. But you didn't know why, all you knew was that suddenly these whips and tops'd come out.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 And did girls play with them, too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, yes. 'Course, that was a dangerous thing in a way, 'cos they'd do it in the street. I mean, a top 
might go out in the road and a horse might be coming along and then the man would have to pull his horse in ever so quickly because a girl would run out, or a boy would run out to get their top. And they used to have ... sometimes they'd stick pieces of c
oloured paper on the top, or chalked with crayons and when it went round it was very pretty. And then, you see, skipping. That used to come round at a certain time of the year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 What time did that come?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 That was in the spring. I don't know what th
e ... I've never read about the real ... any special connection that skipping had, but I have read that about the whips and tops.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did boys skip then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Not much. It was generally girls, but what I do remember is in Colchester on Good Friday... it 
must have been a custom that went back for ages. On Good Friday this Castle Park here would be ... all one part of it would be full of girls and young fellows skipping. And that was always on Good Friday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Was that the skipping where each person has their own rope, or where two people turned the rope?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, yes, yes, most girls had their own rope.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 So it was individual skipping? It wasn't two people turning a rope together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, yes, they used to turn. Oh, yes, they used to do both, a girl would have her own rope. But boys didn't skip much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 But when you used to see them in the Castle Park?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Oh, yes, well what used to happen in the Castle Park, you see, there might be two young fellows turning a rope for a girl, you see, 'cos you al
ways had a big proportion of soldiers in Colchester, and very often it would be soldiers that would turn the rope. But that didn't used to last very long, but it was one of the things on Good Friday. I never know why, except that it was... it may be that 
i
t was the first holiday of the year and people got out. It may have been that, you see, and as they couldn't go anywhere else that was the thing they did. But it used to sort of ... it didn't last, it didn't go on indefinitely. Of course, there was always
 some children would skip, but this particular skipping in the park, I've never seen it mentioned in any books or anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Up to what age would the people in the park be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, they'd be up 'till about the time they got married, you see. 'Cos after they got married they had too many other things to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 They weren't children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
They weren't children, they would be young women, you see, mostly. 'Course, as I say, after a woman got married she didn't have time for anything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 What about the marble season, when was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well, I can't say, exactly, but it was a kind of a ... I think that was in the spring, too. Well, you see, that was a sort of an open air game that you wouldn't play marbles in the very coldest weather, you see, '
cos it was in the open, and so that was probably in the spring.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 What about hopscotch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, yes, they used to play that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 The boys, too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well, sometimes, but that was mostly a girls' game. 'Course, they used to chalk on the pavements, o
r even in the road. You couldn't imagine it now, but still, they did used to do that. And then boys used to have another thing ... that used to in the season, but it wasn't played as much as some things. They had a thing what they call tipca}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12415164\charrsid7434366 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 . It was two p
ieces of ... a long piece of stick and a short piece of stick and they'd put them down in the gutter and then they'd hit the short piece with the long piece and it would throw it up. But there wasn't much in that. It wasn't sort of very popular.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 What about knuckle bones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Yes, all those things used to have their ... well, you know, they all have their day. And another thing they used to have was what they call jack shut-knife. They'd have a pocket knife and sit on a piece of grass, or in a field, 
and there was all sorts of way of getting this knife to stick in the ground, turn it over with the hand and all like that, you see. They were all things that used to be done in spasms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 In the villages some children used to play that one was the fox and the others were the huntsmen, did you play anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well, that was a kind of what we call hide and seek, I suppose. You'd hide up ... I expect that was the same sort of thing, although I haven't heard of it, but we used to play what they
 call hide and seek. Somebody'd hide up and the others would have to try to find them, and all that sort of thing. And then they would have their turn, and all that. And another thing that some boys used to do in the winter, in very cold weather. They'd h
ave a tin, a cocoa tin or something, with holes made in the top and rag inside, alight to warm the hands. 'Course, it was a stick. And they'd also have it on a piece of string, sometimes. Then, of course, there was always conkers in the season.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 What was the season for conkers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well, that was just the thing that has its ... I mean, they play it now. It's just while the season's on, while the conkers are there. They go out and collect the conkers and put them on a bit of string and then hit them, ha
ve a sort of a battle with them. One boy'd got to break the other boy's conkers. I think that's still played to a certain extent. They're just things that have their season.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 What about Guy Fawkes, was that celebrated at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well, in Colch
ester that was quite a biggish day, but not as big as it was in some towns. Not as big as it is in some towns today, 'cos in some towns now it's kept up well. 'Course, you've always had your children that went round to earn a few pennies, but they didn't 
s
tart it about a month beforehand like they do now. And then there used to be in Colchester a gang of men ... they were men, what you call casual labourers, some of them were a little bit simple and they never had real work, you know, they'd sort of do any
t
hing - they used to go round, they'd have a donkey. One of them would ride on the donkey and they would black their faces and dress up and they would go round in shops. They didn't worry people, in the street, but they'd go to shops, and they'd get throug
h all their ... say their piece, as quick as ever they could, 'course, you couldn't understand ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 What sort of thing would they say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well, it used to start off ... if you knew, once you knew what it was supposed to be ... 'course, they used to g
abble it away so often that ... It used to start "Remember, remember the 5}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \super\insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
 November, Gunpowder, treason and plot." And a few lines like that, you see. And then they would ... they'd be in a shop, you see, and all the time they'd be knocking their sticks 
on the floor. Well, the people in the shop - the people who kept the shop - would only be too glad to see the back of them, see them out, that most of them would give them something. And if they didn't give them something they'd give them a jolly good 'bo
o
' for being mean. If they didn't get anything. But of course, there were very few that wouldn't give them something to get rid of them. But of course, they used to make an awful row 'cos all the time they'd be knocking their sticks on the floor. Then of c
o
urse, everybody who could afford it would have fireworks, but of course, they didn't have so many as they have today. And then, perhaps, club together, you see. Several boys would club together, or neighbours would sort of club together and then have a ..
. so they made a bit bigger do of it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 I was interested, reading the notes you made the week before, about the barn and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7434366  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 the circus, and all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, yes, well ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did you ever go to a circus when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 I'm afraid when I was
 young I didn't. 'Cos they used to be rather expensive, well, comparatively expensive and I don't remember going to one at all, because they did used to be expensive.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Did you go to any kind of show?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Yes. What we used to do about the circuses, yo
u see, everybody could see a bit of the circus because they used to have a gigantic procession that went through the main streets and of course, everybody who could - this was held about ... sort of between the school hours, so of course, everybody who co
u
ld would go up and see it. Because, of course, there'd be everything. There'd be elephants and... 'course, that wasn't on the scale of Bertram Mills what is now, not on that scale, not the kind of circus that used to come to these towns. But there used to
 
be another one, Lord John Sangers, that was a big circus. 'Course, they generally only had one day and 'course, they were great events. They were great events. And of course, you see, they had their own band and they would be on these gaily decorated cars
 
going through the town; and then there'd be all the costumes and all the animals. Oh, of course, that used to be a great, a wonderful sight. But as I say, I never went. But we didn't get many entertainments because, for one thing we couldn't afford it, be
c
ause people couldn't, not children. Children didn't have the pocket money and not only that, even in Colchester the entertainment children would have gone to didn't exist. There were no pictures; the theatre, it was sort of too much up, too much up for ch
i
ldren, you know what I mean. The theatre, it wasn't ... plays, the children wouldn't have been able to understand the ordinary plays, unless you had a pantomime at Christmas, that was the only thing. But otherwise, I mean, plays were too ... they weren't 
s
uitable. Well, they weren't considered suitable for children and children wouldn't have enjoyed them there used to be a variety theatre here at the Hippodrome, what's a bingo club now. That was the first variety theatre opened and we did used to go to tha
t sometimes, because, of course, you could go up in the gallery for about 3d..
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Do you remember anything you saw there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, yes. Oh, there used to be some very fine shows, of course. 'Course, up in the gallery you didn't have an upholstered seat t
o sit on, you just sat on the boards. But then, of course, if you could afford to go down in the pits you got a better seat. But of course, they used to have some very fine shows, I mean, because some of the principal comedians used to get here, you see. 
A
nd I can always remember one special thing about one of them. There was a doctor on one occasion - well, he was a so-called doctor (although if he was a real doctor I don't know what he was doing playing ... (laughter)) - but anyway, he claimed to be able
 
to cure people. And there was a boy at school, a boy at the school I went to, he was a cripple and of course his people, like everybody else they were poor. And the teacher was so sorry for him and she paid for him to go to this ... just to see if this do
c
tor could do him any good. And of course, he went up on the stage - you see, people used go up on the stage and I don't know what this doctor used to do, but ... 'course, it didn't make the slightest different to this boy. It didn't make the slightest dif
f
erence to him, I mean, he was just the same afterwards. And of course, these doctors would only be here a week, nobody saw them after that, so the fact that he hadn't cured you didn't cause a lot of bother because he just wasn't there. But that was one th
i
ng. But of course, they did used to get some jolly fine shows. You'd get people riding one wheel bicycles and all sorts of things. Of course, our trouble was that while we went to school we just hadn't got the money, we couldn't go very often. After we le
f
t school, of course, we could afford to go sometimes. Then, of course, you see, when the cinemas came along, they did begin to alter things. But there's one thing I put in my other notes, about the cinemas. I can remember when I was ever so young and I su
p
pose I was just at that age when you can remember, that my sister ... one of my sisters taking me to the Corn Exchange here to what they call Pools Morama, and that was a kind of a ... must have been when the moving pictures was in the very early stages, 
b
ecause I can't remember very much about it expect that they were all horses dashing along and they seemed to be coming towards you. That was called Pools Morama, and I think that that was connected with Ipswich because for years there was a Pools picture 
h
ouse in Ipswich, and I've got an idea that that was the same thing, and then eventually they went over to the ordinary pictures. But you don't hear anything about that sort of thing, but that definitely was so, because I can distinctly remember going and 
I
 know that they were horses. They were men on horses and they seemed to be coming to you. Probably that was something to do with the Boer War. The picture may have been, you see, with all the horses, may have been that. But I can't remember whether they w
ere soldiers on the horses, or not. I couldn't have been very old, but I do remember that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 And you were telling me the very first time I called your very earliest memory. Could you repeat that again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Well, one of the first things I remember, dis
tinctly remember, is my mother lifting me up high so I could see over people's heads to see the Mayor and Corporation and all the ... well, I suppose, the Fire Brigade and all the big ... coming out of one of the local churches which, she told me afterwar
d
s you see, years afterwards when I was thinking about it and said I wondered what it was that she took me to, and she said it was a memorial service for Queen Victoria. And she couldn't go into Church because she'd got me as a baby. But she did tell me ye
a
rs after when I said to her I wondered what it was. But I always remember that there was a huge crowd of people stood outside. I suppose they couldn't all get in the Church, or perhaps some didn't want to, and they just ... 'Cos it used to be an event the
n
, if there was a big do on where the Mayor and Corporation went to Church, even if the people themselves didn't actually go in the Church, they would stand outside and wait to see them all come out and form up. Because, you see, it was an event in their d
rab sort of lives. You see, it was a kind of a treat. I know it sounds pretty simple nowadays, but that's how it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Can you remember being brought up to look up to anybody in the town, or did your parents not have that attitude?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, well, you l
ooked up to anybody who wore a top hat and a frock coat on Sundays. Well, in fact, you looked up to everybody who kept servants.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 You did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, yes, because they were ... well, they were all supposed to be\'85 they were the ... they were the people who ran the country.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 And you were brought up to think that you ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Oh, well, everybody was. Everybody was, because, as I say there was no Labour, well not ... well, there wasn't in these ... And of course, in the villages that was even more so t
han in the town, I mean, it was the squire in the village and the person, they just ran ... they just ran everything. And you'd got to be in their good books, too, if you lived in a village.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 If you met somebody in the town of that standing, what would you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 
Well, if you knew them you would have to raise your cap. You didn't if you didn't know them. But I mean, we always had to raise our cap to the rector, even if we didn't like him. We didn't like him, he wasn't a popular man, but that was the
 custom and you had to raise your cap to the rector. Well, you were supposed to, at any rate. I don't know what the girls did. I expect they used to make a little bow. Of course, people had a ... it wasn't all sham, you know, people had a kind of a real r
e
spect. But of course, as I say, those people did run ... they did run the country, and they governed the towns, I mean, because the working classes weren't capable of doing it. I mean, they weren't educated enough so, I mean, somebody had got to do it. 'C
o
urse, they were all people that'd got ... well, if they weren't wealthy they were all in a pretty substantial way of business. And of course, they used to wear silk hat and frock coats for their great occasions, and of course they used to live in big hous
es and keep servants. And then, of course, their wealth used to ... they used to distribute quite a lot of their wealth in ... they had different forms of charity, keeping the hospitals going and all that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Your own employer, was he ...?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, he was nobody, he was only a self-made man. They were nobody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 You didn't respect him particularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Oh, no. He was ... they were only a couple of self-made people who'd started up in business. Oh, no, that was quite a different thing. Bu
t of course, people did ... where they worked for somebody of real standing, they did used to respect them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid81562 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Do you think they had a different manner from the people who were self-made men?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7038994 EW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11816647\charrsid7434366 Ah, well, of course, a lot of self-made people, they wer
en't educated or anything, they just sort of what you call got on by, perhaps, by hard work, or thrift, or luck. To a certain extent, luck. I mean, one man might launch out in a business and he might do ever so well, while some other same type of man migh
t
 go in the same business and go bankrupt in a short time, you see. It was a question of luck. And of course, a lot of those people, you see, when they started in business on their own, in order to get on they'd go without every form of pleasure 'till they
 
did get on, because they were determined to get on. In fact, they'd got to - either get on or get out. The consequence was, of course, some of them ... 'course, they didn't pay much wages. Those sort of people didn't pay any ... they didn't pay a penny mo
re than they were forced to, but I don't think anybody did in those days. But there was one thing about it, although wages used to be low, there was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16060512\charrsid7434366 1 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
