Oh, yes, and I mean, that often was the case in these big families. And in the First War, when a lot of these young gentlemen from these big houses - of course, they were practically all officers, because in the beginning of the War an o
fficer was a gentleman. Well, he was a gentleman in the sense that he came from where the money was because, of course, then they weren't promoted from the ranks, but later on they just had to be because the others got killed off. Anyway, if the young gen
t
leman from the house got killed in the War, which of course, hundreds and hundreds of them did, well, that was a great grief to the servants. You know, they would feel it, I mean, so they didn't look on it as slavery. Although it was really that, compared
 
with present day conditions. And then, of course, you see, a lot of them - if they came from very poor families, which of course, most people were poor - well, they were living, even as a servant, they were living under much better conditions in a big hou
s
e than they were at home. 'Course, they were under discipline because often there'd be a housekeeper who was a proper martinet. But none the more for that, you see, they were trained and it was considered a good thing to get in a big place and then, perha
ps, to get in a bigger one, still. If you wanted to improve and get in a better place, you see, it gave them standing.
